{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3fc508c6-9066-41e4-a38b-172a837ed548","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is exactly what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — **Reinstalls** the same versions already recorded. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but won't pull newer versions needed by an updated SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK version changed → `workload update`. Installation seems broken/corrupted at the *same* SDK version → `workload repair`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf it still fails afterward, try a clean restore:\n\n```bash\ndotnet clean\ndotnet restore\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ab19ec4f-4196-4b13-b903-4a316ce923ee","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to search any codebase for this.","outputTokens":256,"requestId":"77E7:307F5D:8127C20:8F4FED2:69EABDBA"},"id":"be7ed316-12b5-4d67-9d27-7b5e81706fa3","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:48:02.320Z","parentId":"32bdc782-9ccc-4e18-862b-0898a598ff6d"}
